content.text:
Objects are most commonly created using **object literal** syntax with `{}`. Syntax:
```javascript
const object = {
  propertyName: value,
  methodName: function() {
    // operation
  }
};
```
Properties can be accessed in two ways:
- **Dot notation**: `object.propertyName`
- **Bracket notation**: `object['propertyName']`

content.code:
// Creating an object with object literal
const car = {
  brand: 'Toyota',
  model: 'Camry',
  year: 2020,
  startEngine: function() {
    return 'Engine started!';
  }
};

// Accessing properties
console.log(car.brand); // Toyota
console.log(car['model']); // Camry

// Calling a method
console.log(car.startEngine()); // Engine started!

// Adding a new property
car.color = 'blue';
console.log(car.color); // blue

// Modifying and deleting properties
const person = {
  name: 'Ali',
  age: 25
};

// Modifying a property
person.age = 26;
console.log(person.age); // 26

// Adding a new property
person.job = 'developer';
console.log(person.job); // developer

// Deleting a property
delete person.job;
console.log(person.job); // undefined

content.text:
Functions can be added to objects as **methods**. Methods can work with the object's properties. Syntax:
```javascript
const object = {
  methodName: function() {
    return result;
  }
};
```

content.code:
// Using a method in an object
const student = {
  name: 'Aysu',
  grade: 85,
  getResult: function() {
    return this.name + ' got ' + this.grade + ' points.';
  }
};
console.log(student.getResult()); // Aysu got 85 points.

// Error-prone example
const person = {
  name: 'Veli',
  age: 30
};

// Error: Incorrect property name
console.log(person.nmae); // undefined (should be name instead of nmae)

// Error: Deleting a non-existent property
delete person.job; // No error, but no effect

// Correct approach
if ('name' in person) {
  console.log(person.name); // Veli
}

// Checking for non-existent property
console.log(person.job ? person.job : 'Job not defined'); // Job not defined

// Objects vs. arrays comparison
const personArray = ['Ali', 25, 'developer'];
const personObject = {
  name: 'Ali',
  age: 25,
  job: 'developer'
};

console.log(personArray[0]); // Ali (access by index)
console.log(personObject.name); // Ali (access by name)

